05269nam a22008655i 9780812293272DE-B159720180725125623.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180725s2016    pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122932727 a10.9783/97808122932722doi  a(DE-B1597)487990  a(OCoLC)1046613641  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDS135.S7C64 2017 7aHIS0220002bisacsh 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a946.9/312231 aCohen, Jeremy, eauthor.12aA Historian in Exile :bSolomon ibn Verga, "Shevet Yehudah," and the Jewish-Christian Encounter /cJeremy Cohen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Religious Debate and Disputation -- tChapter 2. Tortosa -- tChapter 3. Talmud and Talmudists -- tChapter 4. Anti-Jewish Libels -- tChapter 5. Martyrs and Martyrdom -- tChapter 6. Conversos and Conversion -- tChapter 7. The Author and His Work: Purpose and Structure -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments  aSolomon ibn Verga was one of the victims of the decrees expelling the Jews from Spain and Portugal in the 1490s, and his Shevet Yehudah (The Scepter of Judah, ca. 1520) numbered among the most popular Hebrew books of the sixteenth century. Its title page lured readers and buyers with a promise to relate "the terrible events and calamities that afflicted the Jews while in the lands of non-Jewish peoples": blood libels, disputations, conspiracies, evil decrees, expulsions, and more.The book itself preserves collective memories, illuminates a critical and transitional phase in Jewish history, and advances a new vision of European society and government. It reflects a world of renaissance, reformation, and global exploration but also one fraught with crisis for Christian majority and Jewish minority alike. Among the multitudes of Iberian Jewish conversos who had received Christian baptism by the end of the fifteenth century, ibn Verga experienced the destruction of Spanish-Portuguese Jewry just as the Catholic Church began to lose exclusive control over the structures of Western religious life; and he joined other Europeans in reevaluating boundaries and affiliations that shaped their identities.In A Historian in Exile, Jeremy Cohen shows how Shevet Yehudah bridges the divide between the medieval and early modern periods, reflecting a contemporary consciousness that a new order had begun to replace the old. Ibn Verga's text engages this receding past in conversation, Cohen contends; it uses historical narrative to challenge regnant assumptions, to offer new solutions to age-old problems, to call Jews to task for bringing much of the hostility toward them upon themselves, and to chart a viable direction for a people seeking a place to call home in a radically transformed world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Jul 2018) 0aBlood accusationzIberian PeninsulavEarly works to 1800. 0aJewsxPersecutionszIberian PeninsulavEarly works to 1800. 0aJewszIberian PeninsulaxHistoryy14th century. 0aReligious disputationszIberian PeninsulavEarly works to 1800. 4aGender Studies. 4aHistory. 4aJewish Studies. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 4aReligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook package 2017-2019z978311065989408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065747040uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812293272423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293272.jpg  a978-3-11-055030-6  Penn Press eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065747-0 